<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-388-836  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 388 836.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  June 26 1989 v6 n25 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sales slowdown prompts DEC to shift workers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>DEC plans to reassign 3,000 to 4,000 manufacturing employees tosales, service and support positions by summer 1990 due to amarket slowdown.andP;  The reassignment will occur at all 35manufacturing plants.andP;  1,000 to 2,000 manufacturing jobs areexpected to disappear in fiscal 1991.andP;  The sales unit will undergoa reorganization and be headed by VP of US sales and service DavidGrainger.andP;  DEC's earnings for 3rd qtr 1989 were down 16 percentand are expected to drop further.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (personnel management).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     Personnel ManagementReorganizationSales.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Sales Slowdown Prompts DEC To Shift WorkersandM;Faced with a softening market for its computer wares, DEC is taking 3,000 to4,000 employees out of manufacturing positions and reassigning them to sales,service and support areas.andM;The sales force is also undergoing a reorganization, which will divide italong business and industry lines rather than geographical areas, a DECspokeswoman said.andP;  The combined units will report to David Grainger, DECsvice president of U.S.andP;  sales and services.andM;The job shifts are expected to be completed within the next year; another1,000 to 2,000 manufacturing jobs will disappear in fiscal 1991, thespokeswoman said.andM;The redeployment will take place at all 35 of DEC's manufacturing plantsworldwide.andM;At present, 33,800 of DEC's 125,500 employees hold manufacturing positions.andM;DEC officials are attributing the redeployment to an &quot;increase inmanufacturing efficiency&quot; and the market slowdown.andP;  However, industryanalysts say the changes are dictated mainly by slow sales and predict that asubstantial number of those redeployed will end up leaving DEC.andM;&quot;Obviously, [DEC's] manufacturing is not overburdened, which says that salesare down,&quot; said John Dunkle, vice president of market research companyWorkGroup Technologies in Hampton, N.H.andM;DEC's actions &quot;give the image that DEC is having difficulty in their salescycle,&quot; Dunkle said.andP;  &quot;It could mean that [DEC] needs better [sales]coverage.andP;  Dunkle added that DEC needs to reduce costs and that this latestmove is probably a better option than others DEC is considering, such asearly retirement.andM;&quot;DEC is counting on causing a natural attrition when people are forced tomove from manufacturing into sales,&quot; he said.andM;Last month, DEC announced a wage freeze that will affect all U.S.andP;  employees,beginning July 2.andP;  The freeze, which will last at least three months, is oneof several cost-cutting measures that were discussed within DEC.andM;DEC's earnings for the third quarter ended April 1 were down 16 percent, andU.S.andP;  sales suffered a substantial drop.andP;  Analysts predict that Digital'sfourth quarter, which will end June 30, will show a further drop.andM;&quot;I suspect they're going to be flat or down in the June quarter,&quot; saidWilliam Easterbrook, an analyst at New York investment company Kidder,Peabody.andO;</TEXT></DOC>